ant's formulation of the ethical imperative. mci will be important for scholars across the humanities as they grapple with the increasingly vexed relationship between aesthetics and ethics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAct (Philosophy). 0aCommunicationxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aEthics. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBakhtin, M. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBocharov, S. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolquist, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolquist, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLiapunov, Vadim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiapunov, Vadim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292792739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292792739/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK